Comment: This is an aggressive variation of the Fisher/Reti opening for black, that results in an upset win over a stronger player.  I got lucky, but it is interesting to see that this typically closed, slow, ponderous opening can be played very aggressively, provided white gives you an opening.  He opens with the common e4, to which I often respond with what is perceived be a weak reply, d6.
d4 is also common at this point.  Nf6 is a common reply for this opening, setting up pressure on the e4 pawn.
d4 is also common at this point.  Nf6 is a common reply for this opening, setting up pressure on the e4 pawn.
At this point, e5 is common setting up a series of early maneuvers that can weaken the castle.  But, in this case, white responds with Nc3, a defensive move.
